notes.note: Rec'd estimate from Brown's Chrysler for replacement of both right side cam shafts, phaser, timing chain, and a number of gaskets. Timing chain and labour to do so not covered, phaser and cam shafts are. Asked for current odometer reading, oil change records, ccc's, and findings following diagnostic. M.P.
notes.content: Rec'd estimate from Brown's Chrysler for replacement of both right side cam shafts, phaser, timing chain, and a number of gaskets. Timing chain and labour to do so not covered, phaser and cam shafts are. Asked for current odometer reading, oil change records, ccc's, and findings following diagnostic. M.P.

notes.note: Also now noticed dealer marked up their own oem parts. Called Peel Chrysler and went through every part that is approved on the estimate, and all of the part pricings listed on estimate were inflated. Going to wait for response and then ask them to change the part pricing to msrp as we do not pay mark up on oem parts provided by the dealership. M.P.

notes.note: Craig from Brown's Chrysler responded, customer came in with check engine light and noise from engine bay. Still need to know source of concern, what failed and caused items to need to be replaced. Submitted oil change receipt. Called Peel Chrysler, interval for oil change should be 8,000 - 10,000 km's and 6 months. Invoice within 10,000 km range. Good. Waiting for adjusted part pricing and explanation of source of concern. M.P.

notes.note: Rec'd response, now saying the engine block is required. Says they took it apart (which I find odd, tells me they didn't do a proper and full diagnostic before sending the first estimate for the cams and etc.) and there are metal filings and chunks in the oil pan. Sent pictures, verified, metal in oil pan. Also sent picture of worn cam, easy to see damage. Questioning used engine pricing. $7500 compared to roughly $4200 listing on carpart.com. M.P.

notes.note: Used engine that was quoted has 129,000 km's on it, more than double what customer current has on her vehicle. Cannot go with this option. Checked carpart.com, no other viable listings. All other listings are either more km's than what vehicle currently has by a landslide, or are over 1000 km's away. Going to have to approve claim for long block replacement. M.P.

notes.note:
Good evening Craig, thanks for answering some of my inquiries and for taking the time to speak to me earlier over the phone. I have spoken to my Claims Manager regarding this claim for Samatha, and we have decided to move forward with authorization for the replacement of the long block. We did not feel that it was fair to put an engine in the vehicle with over double the km's, and there are no other good options for used engines, so we want to do right by the customer and get it fixed up properly for her. Please be advised, the customer is responsible for any diagnostic fees, shop supplies, fluids, filters, and environmental fees, and has a $0 deductible. Additionally, we pay out a maximum of $130/h for labour. If you choose to charge the quoted price of $160/h, the customer will be responsible for the difference. The payout is as follows:

Parts-$13,064.15
Labour-$2340.00 (18 x $130/h)
Deductible-$0
Tax-$770.21
Authorization-AJN39FPXY9

Total = $16,174.36

Once the repair is complete, please send us a copy of the final invoice for payment.

Best regards, 


Matthew Puls
Claims Adjuster
